  </section>


  <section xml:id="sec-two-qubit-visual">
    <title>Visualizing two-qubit state</title>

    <p>
      As we learned before, the horizontal line divides between two different
      possible outcomes. If there is no line, then two different qubits are being
      represented.
    </p>

    <!-- <image source="VisualRep_one_vs_two_qubits_OLD.png" width="40%" /> -->
    <image source="VisualRep_one_vs_two_qubits.png" width="50%" />

    <!--
    <sidebyside widths="35% 15% 15% 35%" valign="top">
      <p> </p>

      <image source="Visual_Onebit_50_positive.png" width="10%" />
      <image source="L3-4-twoqubitvisual.png" width="10%" />
      <p> </p>
    </sidebyside>
    -->

    <p> In the images above, the left side is a single qubit in 50/50 superposition. The right side
      is two different qubits, one <m>\ket{0}</m> and the other <m>\ket{1}</m>. </p>

  </section>

  <p>In the diagrams above, you may have noticed that we always placed the <m>-</m> in front of the
    ⚫, and you may have thought: "Could we put the <m>-</m> in front of the ⚪ instead?". The short
    answer is: you can definitely do so! However, the standard convention is to place the negative
    sign in front of the ⚫. With your understanding of global p</p>

</section>
